article.description: David West hit a 20-footer from the top of the key at the buzzer to give New Orleans a 97-96 win over Washington on Monday night, for the Hornets' fourth straight victory.

related.description: The Hornets traded center Maciej Lampe to the Rockets for point guard Moochie Norris.

article.headline: West's buzzer beater lifts Hornets over Wizards
article.linkText: West's buzzer beater lifts Hornets over Wizards
article.story:
OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- David West is making a habit of hitting winning shots. For the third time this season, West won a game for the Hornets in the final second, hitting a 20-footer from the top of the key at the buzzer to give New Orleans a 97-96 victory over Washington on Monday night. West previously made last-second shots to beat Milwaukee on Jan. 30 and Houston on Dec. 28. New Orleans has won eight of its last nine games, including its last four, and moved five games above .500 (28-23) for the first time this season. "The guys have got confidence in me. The coach has got confidence in me," West said. "I felt my nerves a little, but once I got the basketball, I just took my time and knocked the shot down. "It's something you think about when you're a kid, hitting game-winners in the NBA or hitting shots to win the game, no matter what level it is. It's just a lot sweeter when it's up here." All-Star guard Gilbert Arenas scored 43 points to lead Washington, which had its five-game winning streak snapped. With the Wizards trailing by a point in the final seconds, Arenas missed a 23-footer, but after a scramble for the rebound, Antawn Jamison got the basketball and made a 20-footer on the baseline with 0.5 seconds left, putting the Wizards ahead 96-95. After a timeout, New Orleans' Desmond Mason inbounded to West, who swished his jumper to cap a 19-point performance. Game officials reviewed the shot to see if West released the ball in time and ruled that he did. "Shocked? Everyone was shocked," Arenas said. "You were shocked. I was shocked. He was shocked that it went in. It's hard to win or lose a game with 0.5 seconds left, but obviously it happened." The final play was designed for West. "I told David he makes me look good," New Orleans coach Byron Scott said. "I told Kirk [Snyder] to go to the corner, but that David should be able to step back and be open. He stepped up and knocked it down like he's done so many times this season." Arenas, named the Eastern Conference player of the week earlier in the day, scored 40 or more points for the seventh time this season. He became the first player to score 40 points against the Hornets this season, but his streak of consecutive made free throws ended at 49 when he missed one with 8:36 left in the game. "Gilbert had the look tonight," Washington coach Eddie Jordan said. "He is one of the best competitors around. He single-handedly carried us." The Hornets trailed by 19 points moments into the second half and were down by 12 with two minutes to go in the third quarter. New Orleans then went on a 14-2 run and pulled even at 76-76 on a 3-point play by Aaron Williams with 10:09 left in the game. The Hornets took their first lead since the game's early moments at 85-84 with 6:17 left on Williams' 20-footer. New Orleans extended its advantage to 95-90 with 2:11 left, but the Wizards scored the next six points, capped by Jamison's jumper. He finished with 20 points. The rally from 19 points down was the fourth-largest comeback in the Hornets' franchise history. It came despite the absence of star rookie point guard Chris Paul, who missed his third straight game because of bruised ribs. "We keep finding ways to win," Scott said. "Our confidence is sky-high. You think we're dead in a game and we find a way to win." Speedy Claxton, who's starting in place of Paul, collected his second double-double of the season, finishing with 16 points and 10 assists. Led by 20 points from Arenas, the Wizards shot 50 percent from the field in the first half and led 53-36 at halftime. "We gave ourselves a chance and they hit a tough shot at the end," Jordan said. "The credit goes to them."

Game notes
The Hornets traded center Maciej Lampe to the Houston Rockets on Monday for point guard Moochie Norris. Norris arrived at the Ford Center shortly before tipoff and entered the game with 3:20 left in the first quarter, after two other Hornets guards, Claxton and Snyder, picked up two fouls. Norris played six minutes and had three points and one assist. ... Before the game, two Wizards with Oklahoma ties -- Etan Thomas, who played in high school in Tulsa, and Michael Ruffin, who starred at the University of Tulsa -- presented a check to Hornets owner George Shinn for the Hornets' Hoops for Homes initiative. The $100,600 donation by the Wizards will go toward helping build homes for displaced residents of the New Orleans metropolitan area, in partnership with Habitat for Humanity.
